ce:section.ce:para:
The structure of the substance is analyzed by Cu-Kα radiation (
λ = 0.15406 nm
) and the spatial distribution states of the internal atoms are analyzed using X-ray diffraction (XRD, Rigaku) patterns of the crystal formation. X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) of substances is used to analyze the elemental composition, atomic valence, and surface energy state distribution of a sample surface. Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FT-IR) is used for studies such as analysis of changes in functional groups or chemical bonds in the sample, and characterization or quantification of substances. The absorbance of substances at different wavelengths is analyzed using ultraviolet-visible (UV–vis) spectra. Information on the particle structure and composition of substance is obtained from scanning electron microscope images (SEM) and high-resolution transmission electron microscope images (HRTEM). Photoluminescence (PL) spectroscopy is used to quickly and easily characterize the luminescence properties of semiconductor materials. ESR signals were collected in a BRUKE EMXPLUS spectrometer under dark and light conditions using 5,5-dimethyl-1-pyrroline-N-oxide (DMPO) as a spin trap.

A three-electrode system is used on the electrochemical analyzer (CHI650B) to form a circuit for measurement, and thus other electrochemical parameters are known. Mix 15 mg of BC6/BMO sample with 1.5 mL of isopropanol and 32 μL of Nafion. The suspension was then uniformly dropped onto the conductive surface of the pre-treated FTO glass (
20 mm × 10 mm
) and dried in air to obtain a working electrode. The electrolyte was an aqueous solution (80 mL) of Na2SO4 (2.5208 g). The frequency parameter for electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) measurements is set from 1 Hz to 100 KHz. Mott-Schottky (MS) measurements were carried out at 1 kHz and 5 kHz.
